{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627204"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:46:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:46:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17105"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17105"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.29,0.1,0,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9795"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77594"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9795"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17105"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63107"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5057"},{"type":"tags","id":"9878"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23187"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77594"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAdrenaline is an endogenous catecholamine released from the adrenal medulla. Its cardiovascular effects vary depending on the concentration due to differential receptor affinities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the predominant cardiovascular effect of low-dose adrenaline?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peripheral vasoconstriction","Peripheral vasodilation","Coronary vasoconstriction","Decreased cardiac output","Decreased heart rate"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAt low doses, adrenaline predominantly causes \u003Cstrong\u003Eperipheral vasodilation\u003C/strong\u003E through activation of beta-2 receptors in skeletal muscle vasculature. This leads to decreased peripheral vascular resistance and improved skeletal muscle blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripheral vasoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E occurs at higher doses through alpha-1 receptor activation, whereas at low doses the beta-2 effects predominate over alpha-1 effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdrenaline typically increases rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreases cardiac output\u003C/strong\u003E through beta-1 receptor stimulation, which increases both heart rate and contractility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdrenaline stimulates beta-1 receptors in the heart, causing increased heart rate and contractility, not \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased heart rate\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdrenaline causes coronary vasodilation (not \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoronary vasoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E) through beta-2 receptor activation, improving blood flow to cardiac muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe dose-dependent effects of adrenaline are due to different receptor affinities, with beta-2 effects predominating at low doses and alpha-1 effects becoming more prominent at higher doses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Adrenaline is a catecholamine that acts on both alpha and beta adrenergic receptors.","At low doses, adrenaline primarily causes beta-2 effects including bronchodilation and vasodilation.","At high doses, adrenaline causes alpha-1 mediated vasoconstriction and increased blood pressure."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Cryer PE. Adrenaline: a physiological metabolic regulatory hormone in humans?. Int J Obes Relat Metab Disord. 1993;17 Suppl 3:S43-S68."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63107"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17105"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63107"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:08:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T20:09:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9795"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77594"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"de